# Notification Card Scroll-After-Animation

When a notification card (or any element that animates in via `max-height`) is appended to a scrollable container, a **single** `scrollTop = scrollHeight` call before the animation runs is not enough — the container scrolls when the element is still 0px tall, then the card expands off-screen.

## Rule

Always fire a **second** scroll after the `max-height` transition completes, using a `setTimeout` that matches (or slightly exceeds) the transition duration.

## JS Pattern

```js
function appendNotifViewer() {
  // ...build and append the row...
  messagesEl.appendChild(row);

  // First scroll — positions the container at the bottom before animation
  chatContent.scrollTop = chatContent.scrollHeight;

  // Trigger entrance animation, then scroll again once the card has fully expanded
  requestAnimationFrame(() => requestAnimationFrame(() => {
    const card = document.getElementById('notifViewer');
    if (card) card.classList.add('show');
    // Match the max-height transition duration (550ms) + small buffer
    setTimeout(() => { chatContent.scrollTop = chatContent.scrollHeight; }, 560);
  }));
}
```

## Rules

- The `setTimeout` delay must be **≥ the `max-height` transition duration**. Add ~10ms buffer (e.g. 550ms transition → 560ms timeout).
- Always do the first `scrollTop` synchronously after `appendChild` so the container is already near the bottom before the card grows.
- The second scroll goes **inside** the `requestAnimationFrame` callback (after `.show` is added), not outside it.
- This same pattern applies to any element that reveals itself via `max-height` animation — sticky banners, rec cards, toasts, etc.
